After a pathetic pause, as Sanadon re- marks, Horace adheres to the last two causes he had mentioned. He there- fore imputes the civil wars to the Destinies, and to the death of Remus; as if the Destinies had condemned the Romans to expiate the fratricide of that prince by destroying one another with tnelr own arms. This was going very far back in order to remove the idea of the real cause of their present calamities.—Ayunt. “ Harass.”-—18. Scelusque fraternae necis.
